    "body": "@haydenadams checkIfInternal will return false I believe (if using delegatecall). What is the use case for having a check that you are in an internal within a @public?\r\n\r\nTo elaborate, if @public -> call and @private -> delegatecall.\r\n\r\nif `@private checkIfInternal` the above check will fail.\r\nif `@public checkIfInternal` the above check will pass.\r\n\r\nEdit: \r\nFurther investigation let me to believe that delegatecall isn't an option.\r\n\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6917456/43133801-2934ad18-8f40-11e8-8bdb-e07902070e6f.png)\r\nAs that's how we enforce private calls.\r\n\r\nEdit2:\r\nSo the solution I came up with is to pass the original caller (msg.sender or address opcode) through the call as the first (hidden) parameter and keep using the CALL.\r\nWe can then either elect to have `msg.sender` equal the original address, or use a new attribute? Overriding msg.sender seems clearer to me for an *internal call* use case.\r\n\r\n@maurelian @fubuloubu thoughts?\r\n",
